3. **JavaScript Logic**: Use JavaScript to handle the drag and drop functionality. You can use the `dragstart`, `dragover`, `dragenter`, `dragleave`, and `drop` events to manage the drag and drop process.

```javascript
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function() {
  const list = document.getElementById('sortableList');

  list.addEventListener('dragstart', function(event) {
    // Set the data transfer type and the data
    event.dataTransfer.setData('text/plain', event.target.id);
  });

  list.addEventListener('dragover', function(event) {
    // Prevent the default behavior to allow dropping
    event.preventDefault();
  });

  list.addEventListener('dragenter', function(event) {
    // Highlight the target element
    event.target.style.backgroundColor = 'lightblue';
  });

  list.addEventListener('dragleave', function(event) {
    // Remove the highlight from the target element
    event.target.style.backgroundColor = '';
  });

  list.addEventListener('drop', function(event) {
    // Prevent the default behavior to allow dropping
    event.preventDefault();

    // Get the id of the dragged element
    const id = event.dataTransfer.getData('text/plain');

    // Find the dragged element
    const draggedElement = document.getElementById(id);

    // Find the target element where the drop occurred
    const targetElement = event.target;

    // Check if the target element is a list item
    if (targetElement.tagName === 'LI') {
      // Insert the dragged element before the target element
      targetElement.parentNode.insertBefore(draggedElement, targetElement);
    }
  });
});
```

This code sets up a basic drag-and-drop functionality for a list of items. When an item is dragged, it is highlighted, and when dropped, it is inserted before the target element. This is a simple implementation and can be expanded with additional features such as reordering within the list or handling multiple lists.

To create a new DOM element, set its attributes, and append it to a parent element, you can use the `document.createElement()`, `setAttribute()`, and `appendChild()` methods in JavaScript. Here's a step-by-step guide with code examples:

